Introduction

For this project, I would like to focus on who has I been communicated with the most during the time period that the data was extracted. I have categorized the email I have been receiving, the number of characters and the time period. My aim for this project is for the person who glance at my charts and will obtain as much information as possible.

For the first chart: I would like the reader to have an overall information of who has been sending me emails and under which group such as, from Canvas, universities, between fellow students and other emails. So this allow the reader to have a quick glance and easily see who I have been receiving emails from the most and the least. To create the chart, I picked a bar chart and reorder them from the accending order. I removed the grey background so that the colour theme from viridislite package poped but I left the gridlines on the chart so it is easy to read the figure.

For the second chart: I did stacked bar chart so that the reader can have a quick glance and see who sent me the most emails during each month. The colour codings for each sender corresponding to the previous chart1.

For the third chart: I did scatter plot with triangle indicating the mean character length. This chart I would like to explore with adding multiple layers on ggplot.The scatter plot allows the reader to see the distribution of the number of character.

For the animation graph, I was initially wanting the animated stacked bar chart during the time period to see how the incoming email changes during the time period and see how has sent me the emails the most. But after tring and figuring out the transition_* layer, state and other related functions, I decided to go with a simple line chart with the stacked bar graphs animated together. It is not what I was hoping to achieved but at least the reader can see the incoming emails change over the time period and the proportion of sender.

Visualisations

Chart 1 showed the people who sent the email to my email and ranking each group by the ascending order.

Chart 2 showed the total number of emails received in each month with the proportion of the senders. Chart3 showed the distributions of the number of characters in the email sent by each sender groups with trigles indicate the mean value. The animation shows the changes in incoming emails throughout the time period.

Learning reflection

For this project, I learnt the power of ggplot functions where it can create so many different data visualisations according to the information we would like to deliver. With the story I would like to tell, I had to be critical to the designs of my charts and how I could deliver the most information in a quick glance. In this project, I was working under the inspiration of this following quote “A picture is worth a thousand words”. So I tried my best to be creative with my chart designs.

For the creativity in this project, I used ViridisLite package so I could use a nice colour pallate for my charts. It assigned a particular colour to each group of sender which was used through out all the charts. This way, the reader could recognize the sender group easily.

For the future content, I would like to learn more on the power of RStudio and r language and what else we can use for data and analysis.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(gganimate)
library(viridisLite)



#story: In each month, who did I receive email from the most, and who wrote the longest email

url <-("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/e/2PACX-1vSDsPLEUPFsCyTmHqpDK0eiw0zkXLOsOEfSLH3upravNJ4Usxp8lG5obLMnJynPsZ9P5mZycP4DPj4F/pub?output=csv")

email_data <- read_csv(url)

#removing sensitive information

email_data <- email_data %>% mutate(sender_email = case_when(
                      str_detect(email_from, "@aucklanduni.ac.nz") ~ "student",
                      str_detect(email_from, "rrav628") ~ "me",
                      str_detect(email_from, "auckland.ac.nz") ~ "Teaching staff and university staff",
                      str_detect(email_from, "piazza") ~ "piazza",
                      str_detect(email_from, "grammarly") ~ "grammarly",
                      str_detect(email_from, "notifications@instructure.com") ~ "Canvas",
                      TRUE ~ "other"),
                      receieve_email = case_when(
                        str_detect(email_from, "@aucklanduni.ac.nz") ~ "student",
                        str_detect(email_from, "rrav628") ~ "me",
                        str_detect(email_from, "auckland.ac.nz") ~ "Teaching staff and university staff",
                        str_detect(email_from, "piazza") ~ "piazza",
                        str_detect(email_from, "grammarly") ~ "grammarly",
                        str_detect(email_from, "notifications@instructure.com") ~ "Canvas",
                        TRUE ~ "other"),
                      email_character = nchar(email_body))

#remove emails and content                      
email_data <- email_data[,c(-1,-2,-4)]

#bar graph of sender

sender <- email_data %>%
  count(sender_email)

ggplot() +
  geom_col(data = sender,
           aes(x = reorder(sender_email, n),
               y = n))


#fit viridis colour to ggplot

g1 <- ggplot() +
  geom_col(data = sender,
           aes(x = reorder(sender_email, n),
               y = n)) 

g1 + scale_fill_viridis_d()

#didn't work

#instead of count, try group_by instead

sender2 <- email_data %>%
  group_by(sender_email) %>% summarise(n = n())

g2 <- ggplot() +
  geom_col(data = sender2,
           aes(x = reorder(sender_email, n),
               y = n,
               fill = viridis(6, option = "D")))

g2 + scale_fill_viridis_d()

#try 2
g3<- ggplot() +
  geom_col(data = sender2,
           aes(x = sender_email,
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email))

g3 + scale_fill_viridis_d()

#try3 - the final ones

g4 <- ggplot() +
  geom_col(data = sender2,
           aes(x = reorder(sender_email, n),
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme_minimal() + 
  guides(fill = "none") + 
  labs(x = "sender",
       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The amount of emails sent by the following senders")

ggsave("chart1.png", plot = g4)
  
#proportion of sender in each month

group_email_month <- email_data %>%
  count(email_month, sender_email)

#create bar chart with geom_bar

ggplot(data = group_email_month) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = email_month, 
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack")

#create bar chart with geom_col
ggplot(data = group_email_month) +
  
  geom_col(aes(x = email_month, 
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack")


#fit viridis colour palette, finall

group_email_month <- email_data %>%
  count(email_month, sender_email)

chart2 <- ggplot(data = group_email_month) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = email_month, 
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(x = "Month",
       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The number of emails in each month")
  
ggsave("chart2.png", plot = chart2)

#bar graph of email coming in each month

email_length <- email_data %>%
  group_by(sender_email) %>%
  summarise(mean_character = mean(email_character))

#visualise email length, final
#base layer
chart3 <- ggplot() +
  #add jitter
  geom_jitter(data = email_data,
              aes(x = email_character, y = sender_email),
              height = 0.2) + 
  
  #later 2 - mean indicator using geompoint
  geom_point(data = email_length,
             aes(x = mean_character, 
                 y = reorder(sender_email, -mean_character),
             colour = sender_email),
             size = 5,
             shape = 17) +
  scale_colour_viridis_d() +
  theme_minimal() + 
  guides(fill = "none") + 
  labs(x = "The number of characters in each email by different groups of sender",
       y = "character number",
       title = "The number of characters in each email by different groups of sender")
  
ggsave("chart3.png", plot = chart3, width = 8, height = 8)

# goal to create date time series graph

months_data <- email_data %>%
  mutate(incoming_email = email_data$email_date %>% str_sub(1,10) %>% as.Date(tryFormats = "%d/%m/%Y")) %>%
           count(incoming_email)

ggplot(months_data) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = incoming_email,
                y = n))

Sys.setlocale("LC_TIME", "C")           

months_data2 <- email_data %>%
  mutate(incoming_email = email_data$email_date %>% str_sub(1,10) %>% as.Date(tryFormats = "%d/%m/%Y")) %>%
  count(incoming_email, sender_email)

#try line graph - too messy
ggplot(months_data2) +
  geom_line(aes(x = incoming_email,
                y = n,
                color = sender_email))

#try bar graph
ggplot(months_data2) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = incoming_email,
                y = n,
                fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack") + 
  scale_fill_viridis_d() + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(x = "The number of characters in each email by different groups of sender",
       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The number of email received in each day during February - May")
  

#create animation

animation <- ggplot(months_data2) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = incoming_email,
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack") + 
  scale_fill_viridis_d() + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  transition_states(incoming_email) +
  labs(x = "The number of characters in each email by different groups of sender",
       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The number of email received in each day during February - May")
animate(animation)

#change to transition_reveal

animation2 <- ggplot(months_data2) +
  
  #layer1 create stacked bar chart
  geom_bar(aes(x = incoming_email,
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email,
               group = incoming_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack") + 
  scale_fill_viridis_d() + 
  transition_reveal() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "The number of characters in each email by different groups of sender",
       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The number of email received in each day during February - May")

animation2 + 
  transition_reveal(incoming_email)
animate(animation2)

#transition layers

animation3 <- ggplot(months_data2) +
  
  #layer1 create stacked bar chart
  geom_bar(aes(x = incoming_email,
               y = n,
               fill = sender_email),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "stack") +

       y = "number of emails",
       title = "The number of email received in each day during February - May")

animation3 +

animate(animation3)
